but treated as unwelcome aliens, this contingent of Japanese Americans—one in four U.S.-born Nisei—came in search of better lives but instead encountered a world shaped by increasingly volatile relations between the U.S. and Japan. Based on transnational and bilingual research in the United States and Japan, Michael R. Jin recuperates the stories of this unique group of American emigrants at the crossroads of U.S. and Japanese empire. From the Jim Crow American West to the Japanese colonial frontiers in Asia, and from internment camps in America to Hiroshima on the eve of the atomic bombing, these individuals redefined ideas about home, identity, citizenship, and belonging as they encountered multiple social realities on both sides of the Pacific. Citizens, Immigrants, and the Stateless examines the deeply intertwined histories of Asian exclusion in the United States, Japanese colonialism in Asia, and volatile geopolitical changes in the Pacific world that converged in the lives of Japanese American migrants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCitizenshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericanszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericanszWest (U.S.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aStateless personsxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransnationalismxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJapanese Americans. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican West.  aCitizenship.  aDiaspora.  aImmigration.  aJapanese American.  aKibei.  aMigration.  aNisei.  aPacific.  aWorld War II.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362832840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628328/o